{"type":"item.completed","item":{"id":"item_23","type":"command_execution","command":"/bin/bash -lc \"sed -n '1,140p' references_cache/PMID_19887069.md\"","aggregated_output":"---\nreference_id: PMID:19887069\ntitle: Role of vesicle tethering factors in the ER-Golgi membrane traffic.\nauthors:\n- Sztul E\n- Lupashin V\njournal: FEBS Lett\nyear: '2009'\ndoi: 10.1016/j.febslet.2009.10.083\nkeywords:\n- Animals\n- Biological Transport\n- Cytoplasmic Vesicles/metabolism\n- Endoplasmic Reticulum/metabolism\n- Golgi Apparatus/metabolism\n- Humans\n- Intracellular Membranes/metabolism\ncontent_type: abstract_only\n---\n\n# Role of vesicle tethering factors in the ER-Golgi membrane traffic.\n**Authors:** Sztul E, Lupashin V\n**Journal:** FEBS Lett (2009)\n**DOI:** [10.1016/j.febslet.2009.10.083](https://doi.org/10.1016/j.febslet.2009.10.083)\n\n## Content\n\n1. FEBS Lett. 2009 Dec 3;583(23):3770-83. doi: 10.1016/j.febslet.2009.10.083.\nEpub  2009 Nov 1.\n\nRole of vesicle tethering factors in the ER-Golgi membrane traffic.\n\nSztul E(1), Lupashin V.\n\nAuthor information:\n(1)Department of Cell Biology, University of Alabama at Birmingham, 1918 \nUniversity Boulevard, Birmingham, AL 35294, USA.\n\nTethers are a diverse group of loosely related proteins and protein complexes \ngrouped into three families based on structural and functional similarities. A \nwell-accepted role for tethering factors is the initial attachment of transport \ncarriers to acceptor membranes prior to fusion. However, accumulating evidence \nindicates that tethers are more than static bridges. Tethers have been shown to \ninteract with components of the fusion machinery and with components involved in \nvesicle formation. Tethers belonging to the three families act at the same stage \nof traffic, suggesting that they mediate distinct events during vesicle \ntethering. Thus, multiple tether-facilitated events are required to provide \nselectivity to vesicle fusion. In this review, we highlight findings that \nsupport this model.\n\nDOI: 10.1016/j.febslet.2009.10.083\nPMCID: PMC2788073\nPMID: 19887069 [Indexed for MEDLINE]","exit_code":0,"status":"completed"}}
{"type":"item.started","item":{"id":"item_24","type":"command_execution","command":"/bin/bash -lc \"sed -n '1,140p' references_cache/PMID_19575650.md\"","aggregated_output":"","exit_code":null,"status":"in_progress"}}
{"type":"item.completed","item":{"id":"item_24","type":"command_execution","command":"/bin/bash -lc \"sed -n '1,140p' references_cache/PMID_19575650.md\"","aggregated_output":"---\nreference_id: PMID:19575650\ntitle: Tethering factors as organizers of intracellular vesicular traffic.\nauthors:\n- Yu IM\n- Hughson FM\njournal: Annu Rev Cell Dev Biol\nyear: '2010'\ndoi: 10.1146/annurev.cellbio.042308.113327\nkeywords:\n- Animals\n- Multiprotein Complexes/metabolism\n- SNARE Proteins/metabolism\n- Transport Vesicles/metabolism\n- Vesicular Transport Proteins/metabolism\ncontent_type: abstract_only\n---\n\n# Tethering factors as organizers of intracellular vesicular traffic.\n**Authors:** Yu IM, Hughson FM\n**Journal:** Annu Rev Cell Dev Biol (2010)\n**DOI:** [10.1146/annurev.cellbio.042308.113327](https://doi.org/10.1146/annurev.cellbio.042308.113327)\n\n## Content\n\n1. Annu Rev Cell Dev Biol. 2010;26:137-56. doi: \n10.1146/annurev.cellbio.042308.113327.\n\nTethering factors as organizers of intracellular vesicular traffic.\n\nYu IM(1), Hughson FM.\n\nAuthor information:\n(1)Department of Molecular Biology, Princeton University, Princeton, New Jersey \n08544, USA.\n\nIntracellular trafficking entails the budding, transport, tethering, and fusion \nof transport vesicles and other membrane carriers. Here we review recent \nprogress toward a mechanistic understanding of vesicle tethering. The known \ntethering factors are large complexes important for one or more intracellular \ntrafficking pathways and are capable of interacting directly with many of the \nother principal components of the cellular trafficking machinery. Our review \nemphasizes recent developments in the in vitro reconstitution of vesicle \ntethering and the structural characterization of multisubunit tethering factors. \nThe combination of these and other approaches has led to exciting progress \ntoward understanding how these essential nanomachines work.\n\nDOI: 10.1146/annurev.cellbio.042308.113327\nPMID: 19575650 [Indexed for MEDLINE]","exit_code":0,"status":"completed"}}
